evapotranspiration and shrinkage of the wetted will area will increase \uf0b7 Shallower and edges of the wetland will tend to dry out faster H11 M 6The system is a mosaic of open water, grasslands and flooded forest with mixed exposure to high temperatures, some shading. 7Peat land area is unique in Laos, if it dries out it will be lost. Large wetlands in Laos are also rare. 8The mosaic of the wetland allows for flexibility in adapting to changes each year, grassland especially is able to reestablish itself. But note that peatland may have less adaptive capacity, especially if it dries out for too long. 9The rainfall in dry season does not do much to affect the extent of the wetland, but the lower rainfall in January to April, and higher temperatures increase the evapotranspiration. 10The shallower parts of the wetland and edges will be sensitive changes in evapotranspiration and falling soil moisture content. 11Wetland ecosystem cannot do very much to adapt to reduction in dry season rainfall, but shows strong resilience when the rains come and the wetlands are wetted again. 93 increases by about 11% in May Increase in rainfall in wet season \uf0b7 10% increase overall in wet season from May to October VH12 L13 H \uf0b7 Flooded area will increase in size, more open water \uf0b7 Some areas will become deeper \u2013 if grassland area, it may be the grassland will not survive \uf0b7 Large trees will survive, in the long term young trees will not grow in the deeper area \uf0b7 Some shift in the distribution of different habitats, but not a major shift H1415 M Change and shift in events Increased frequency and intensity of storms \uf0a7 One more heavy rainfall event per year \uf0a7 Intensity of heaviest storm increases from 120 to 144mm H16 L17 M \uf0b7 Storm events will only have temporary effect upon the wetland \uf0b7 Some damage to trees H18 M Increased risk of flooding \uf0b7 During August the maximum monthly rainfall is likely to increase from 398 to 425 mm \uf0b7