Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e2cfb3495c5963209cc46161b4737afb1112b7814286943e3acb1773e448f461"}, "3": {"node_id": "aec08180-9ad4-493e-ac70-a9136d340c0b", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/twenty-two-stories-conservation-africa-key-elements-effective-and-well", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "339aa1a4e37bfc31062ca9b0ea4b90a7fea3e4592103f2d84a4d5a0234074adb"}}, "hash": "35dfa9c9b8033a2a80468d939977f49480c8d83929ecf3619820c5a4adc27494", "text": "CONTENTS Preface by Geoffroy Mauvais iii Acknowledgements iv List of authors v Introduction: the evolution of protected areas\u2019 governance in Africa ix PART 1 Protected areas managed by the government: changes of practices and scales 1 From top down to bottom-up BINTA BA DIAW 2 Improving PAs\u2019 management effectiveness VIRAT KOOTSOSITSE MOTSHEREGANYI 5 Recipe for a good couple life NICHOLAS DE GOEDE 8 Beyond borders LESEHO SELLO 12 Building peace on Nature conservation GEORGES MUAMBA 15 PART 2 Toward broader protected areas governance: more stakeholders for better results 18 From hunting to mapping JEAN-BRUNO NGOUGNOGBIA 19 When women take the lead DANCILLA MUKAKAMARI 22 When private landowners commit to conserving nature NILS ODENDAAL 25 Stakeholders\u2019 collaboration driven by an international NGO DANIEL MARNEWICK 29 Involving youth to build the future MARY MARGARET OTIENO 32 ! !!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! ii!!Content! PART 3 Reinforcing legitimacy of protected areas: working with the local communities 35 Empowering communities INZA KONE 36 When hunters enter conservation MARTIAL KOUDERIN 40 Widening consultation for strengthening biodiversity conservation corridors TOGARASEI FAKARAYI 43 Marine conservation by and for fishermen SALATOU SAMBOU 46 National recognition of local traditions JOSEPH ITONGWA MUKUMO 48 Because conservation has to make concessions MARTIN MULAMA 50 PART 4 Conservation and development, two faces of the same coin: protected areas as a revenue catalyst 53 Financial challenges of conservation FREDDY MANONGI 54 Ecotourism as a tool for local development SAKHILE NSUKWINI 57 Auto-regulation by communities for marine conservation ALASDAIR HARRIS 60 Ensuring sustainability of natural resources uses ALEXIS KABORE 63 Counting and accounting for good decision-making RAVAKA RANAIVOSON 66 Development and conservation, a matter of concessions TOM OBONG OKELLO 70 Contacts 74 TWENTY-TWO CHAMPIONS FROM AFRICA The 6th World Parks Congress was organized in Sydney, Australia, in November 2014. More than 6,000 people from 170 countries attended this event which enabled conservation professionals to take stock of progress made since the previous congress, in Durban, South Africa, in 2003. And also to discuss the challenges that have emerged since then. From this point of view, Africa is particularly under pressure. The causes are many and have been the subject of numerous evaluations, some of them led by the IUCN Program on African Protected Areas & Conservation (IUCN-Papaco) since 2006. In addition to poor management effectiveness, one of these causes is the weak governance of most PAs, which negatively impacts on all activities that are conducted on the ground. That is why IUCN-Papaco focuses on governance in the context of a roadmap for Protected Areas: more ethical behavior, more legitimacy for decisions, accountability and transparency in the way they are made, more stakeholders involved, more professionalism for managers, more ownership of the tremendous assets that PAs offer, more recognition for those who succeed, more durability for conservation... these are the directions that this roadmap tries to promote for the future of conservation in Africa. To ensure a good participation of Africa at the congress, we launched a call for proposals open to stakeholders involved in and around PAs. The objective was to prepare key messages that would be brought to the congress by a team of conservationists coming from all over the continent. This was a great success and we received more than 150 proposals (from 33 African countries). After a rigorous selection process, 22 candidates were selected and became our \u201cchampions\u201d. Their messages cover all aspects of PA good governance, PA management efficiency and the sustainability of conservation. Together, they deliver a comprehensive and consistent message about the present and the future of protected areas on the continent and were to some extent \"the voice of Africa\" at the congress. All these champions indeed travelled to Sydney and were able to speak clearly and loudly about conservation in Africa. And they were listened to. This book is about this fantastic journey. It gathers all these experiences and tells you the story of our 22 champions, their messages and their hope.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "aec08180-9ad4-493e-ac70-a9136d340c0b": {"__data__": {"id_": "aec08180-9ad4-493e-ac70-a9136d340c0b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/twenty-two-stories-conservation-africa-key-elements-effective-and-well", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Twenty-two stories of conservation in Africa : key elements for effective and well-governed protected areas", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/twenty-two-stories-conservation-africa-key-elements-effective-and-well", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "Internat