Papaco\u2019s - sometimes heavy - demands, they answered to all our expectations and their reactivity and optimism made it very pleasant for us to work with all of them. Finally, we would like to thank Guy Broucke, Christine Mentzel and Stella Musiiwa from IUCN as well as Daniel Marnewick from BirdLife South Africa who gently offered to proofread this book and helped us to finalise it. ! ! AUTHORS Binta Ba DIAW, Marine Community Based Protected Areas Department, Senegal Holding a Masters degree in protected areas\u2019 management, Binta has been working in the field of conservation since 2004. She first worked, for 4 years, on sustainable forest management by communities in south-east Senegal and then joined the Senegal Directorate of National Parks in 2008. In 2012, when the Marine Community Based Protected Areas Department was created, she was offered to be part of the team in charge of backing the management of the 9 marine protected areas of Senegal. Nicholas DE GOEDE, /Ai/Ais-Richtersveld Transfrontier Park, South Africa Nicholas is the park manager of the South African side of the /Ai/Ais-Richtersveld Transfrontier Park. Nick has been working with Transfrontier Conservation Areas for many years. He worked for the Natal Parks Board for 16 years and then for Ezemvelo KwaZulu- Natal Wildlife (Maloti-Drakensberg and Lubombo TFCAs). He joined the Ai/Ais- Richtersveld park 6 years ago and is in charge of various aspects related to conservation, technical services, human resources, administration and tourism. Togarasei FAKARAYI, BirdLife Zimbabwe, Zimbabwe Togarasei is Programme Manager at BirdLife Zimbabwe, responsible for stakeholder capacity building and engagement in and around Important Birds and Biodiversity Areas (IBBAs). He has over 9 years experience working with communities, government and civil society organizations in driving conservation work in IBBAs and other priority conservation sites. Alasdair HARRIS, Blue Ventures, Madagascar Marine ecologist Alasdair Harris has spent the past decade developing conservation initiatives in the Indian Ocean, and led his first marine research expedition to Madagascar in 2001. Within Blue Ventures, Alasdair is responsible for coordinating conservation and research activities, leading an interdisciplinary and international team of scientists, educators and conservation practitioners. His work focuses on developing scalable solutions to marine environmental challenges, in particular pioneering market-based approaches that make marine conservation make economic sense to coastal communities. Joseph ITONGWA MUKUMO, ICCAs Consortium for Central Africa, DRC A native Batwa from Walikale, a town located in the border of Kahuzi-Bi\u00e9ga National Park in North Kivu, Joseph has been involved in the fight for indigenous people rights for years. As an active member in various local, national and regional organisations that promote indigenous participation in natural resources governance, he had the chance to represent his peers at several international meetings and to promote the implementation of Indigenous peoples' and community conserved territories and areas (ICCAs) in Central Africa.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3e0b593b-2676-49a1-a249-d17104f36603": {"__data__": {"id_": "3e0b593b-2676-49a1-a249-d17104f36603", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/twenty-two-stories-conservation-africa-key-elements-effective-and-well", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Twenty-two stories of conservation in Africa : key elements for effective and well-governed protected areas", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/twenty-two-stories-conservation-africa-key-elements-effective-and-well", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a3b03facba4ce5d907440c744218e9e4c4e8510a39634a3e8e350b4951387b96"}, "2": {"node_id": "c156c970-c7f5-4509-87d0-4eec39e9e94c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/twenty-two-stories-conservation-africa-key-elements-effective-and-well", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fe1526bedc656775bf05ef644052d12f884a4175b745390aa3ec64170e6edfd5"}}, "hash": "29dc992bad55cace5d536e2b44b09b2f52c32529a20e3b38bd447f9f7695ab06", "text": "Alexis KABORE, Association Faune et D\u00e9veloppement au Burkina (AFAUDEB), Burkina Faso In 1995, while he was still a student, Alexis worked with the communities neighbouring the reserves of Eastern Burkina Faso and soon realized that these communities were neither benefiting from the conservation of the reserves\u2019 resources or participating in their protection. He thus founded, in 2008, the Wildlife and Development Association of Burkina Faso (l\u2019Association Faune et D\u00e9veloppement au Burkina - AFAUDEB) which aims at conserving Burkina Faso\u2019s biodiversity and protected areas in order to promote sustainable development. Inza KONE, Centre Suisse de Recherches Scientifiques, Ivory Coast Inza holds a PhD in Primate Conservation Biology from the Universit\u00e9 F\u00e9lix Houphou\u00ebt- Boigny (UFHB), Abidjan, C\u00f4te d\u2019Ivoire. This very first home-grown primatologist is currently a Senior Lecturer at the UFHB and the Scientific Director of the Centre Suisse de Recherches Scientifiques en C\u00f4te d\u2019Ivoire (CSRS), Abidjan. He is a member of (i) the Advisory Board of the Institute for Breeding Rare and Endangered African Mammals (IBREAM), Utrecht, the Netherlands, (ii) the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "adee0c09-459d-466d-beb1-cdc698bca6f4": {"__data__": {"id_": "adee0c09-459d-466d-beb1-cdc698bca6f4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/twenty-two-stories-conservation-africa-key-elements-effective-and-well", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Twenty-two stories of conservation in Africa : key elements for effective and well-governed protected areas", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/twenty-two-stories-conservation-africa-key-elements-effective-and-well", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "70ce2e849e0c21b201efee7d18cd0857cd95a011344271368fa210b5e5894f7d"}, "3": {"node_id": "e8e50107-78e4-4a1c-a815-c9d0156a97cb", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/twenty-two-stories-conservation-africa-key-elements-effective-and-well", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ecca7c1150f94b1feae901967dd66dcf2ffe761509046e97d04af4ec470ef662"}}, "hash": "d2147e1b7683be119a332895e1cee945bfb9ecbb6dc901eb38c021921a9ce37f", "text": "IUCN SSC Primate Specialist Group, (iii) IUCN SSC Hippo Specialists Group, (iv) the Conservation Committee of the International Primatological Society. His work focuses on the management of natural resources and the conservation of endangered large mammal species, especially primates, by linking ecology, economics, and culture for community empowerment. Martial KOUDERIN, CREDI-ONG, Benin An agronomist specialised in aquatic ecosystems management, Martial is the Executive Director and one of the founders of CREDI-ONG, a Beninese conservation NGO that he and his partners funded in 2005 with the goal to empower communities in resources management. He is also the president of the National Fish Farmers Federation of Benin (F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Nationale des Pisciculteurs du B\u00e9nin - FENAPIB). Freddy MANONGI, Ngorongoro Conservation Area Authority, Tanzania Freddy is Conservator of the Ngorongoro Conservation Area Authority (NCAA) in Tanzania. Before that, he was the Acting Principal of the College of African Wildlife Management (MWEKA) in Tanzania and worked as Environmental Advisor in the Ministry of Finance and Development Planning in Botswana. Over the years, Freddy has helped the Ministry for Natural Resources and Tourism in Tanzania to identify, design, appraise and develop monitoring and evaluation tools for protected areas\u2019 governance and planning frameworks in Tanzania. Daniel MARNEWICK, BirdLife South Africa, South Africa Daniel is a sociologist and conservationist rolled into one. He has been working for BirdLife South Africa since 2006, and managing their Important Bird and Biodiversity Areas (IBAs) Programme since 2009. This Programmes aims to ensure the correct management and protection of these key sites and habitats throughout South Africa for the benefit of birds and other associated biodiversity and ecosystem services. Virat Kootsositse MOTSHEREGANYI, BirdLife Botswana, Botswana When he graduated in ecology and environmental management and in strategic management, Kootsositse joined the field of environmental conservation where he has now been working for 10 years. After the Department of Wildlife and National Parks and the Botswana Tourism Organisation, he joined Birdlife where he now coordinates projects implemented by BirdLife on behalf of the Government of Botswana. Georges MUAMBA, Greater Virunga Transboundary Collaborative, DRC Georges is currently the executive secretary of the Greater Virunga Transboundary Collaboration (Collaboration Transfrontaliere du Grand Virunga - GVTC) between Rwanda, the Democratic Republic of Congo and Uganda. Before that, he gained experience in international management as he was in charge of international cooperation and planning of the ! !!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! vi!!Authors! Congolese Institute for Nature Conservation (Institut Congolais pour la Conservation de la Nature - ICCN) for 10 years. Dancilla MUKAKAMARI, ARECO-RWANDA NZIZA, Rwanda Dancilla is the National Coordinator of the environmental and development organization Rwandese Association of Ecologists (ARECO-RWANDA NZIZA). She has several years of experience in sustainable natural resource management and biodiversity conservation and is, in particular, involved in community and women empowerment for sustainable development in Rwanda\u2019s protected areas. Dancilla is passionately involved in networks and working groups on gender and conservation as well as environment protection at national, regional and international levels. Martin MULAMA, OlPejeta Conservancy, Kenya Martin is a conservation biologist with a PhD from University of Eldoret (Kenya). He previously worked for the Kenya Wildlife Service where, in his final six years, he was the Senior Scientist heading the National Rhino Programme. Martin has specialist training in different aspects of natural resource conservation and management. He joined the Ol Pejeta Conservancy as the Chimpanzee Sanctuary Manager and Technical Advisor in March 2006 and was promoted to the position of Chief Conservation Officer in October 2010, a position he holds to date. Jean-Bruno NGOUGNOGBIA, Maison de l\u2019Enfant et de la Femme Pigm\